    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve"><head>Text</head><ab><lb n="1"/>
                Victoriae <supplied reason="lost"><expan><abbr>d</abbr><ex>omini</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>n</abbr><ex>ostri</ex></expan></supplied> <lb n="2"/><del rend="erasure">[Gallieni Pii Felicis</del>] <lb n="3"/><supplied reason="lost"><expan><abbr>Aug</abbr><ex>usti</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>Germ</abbr><ex>anici</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>max</abbr><ex>imi</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>pont</abbr><ex>ificis</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>max</abbr><ex>imi</ex></expan></supplied> <lb n="4"/><supplied reason="lost">et <expan><abbr>P</abbr><ex>ubli</ex></expan> Licini Corneli</supplied> <lb n="5"/><supplied reason="lost">Salonini <expan><abbr>nob</abbr><ex>ilissimi</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>Caes</abbr><ex>aris</ex></expan></supplied> <lb n="6"/><supplied reason="lost"><expan><abbr>ceterisq</abbr><ex>ue</ex></expan> dis <expan><abbr>deabusq</abbr><ex>ue</ex></expan></supplied> <lb n="7"/>sacrum
            </ab></div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>7 fragments, 5 of them are matching. Maybe the name was erased in 268-269, when Postumus was ruling this area. Van Berchem thinks that maybe one of the 2 not matching fragments could belong to another inscription, because of the different orientation of the stone veins. The only thing that can be read is part of a X and then a second line is erased.</p>
            </div>
